Abstract
The integration of Artificial Intelligence (AI) into safety-critical automotive systems presents a fundamental challenge: ISO 26262, the international standard for functional safety in road vehicles, was designed for systems with predictable, bounded, deterministic behavior. Stochastic AI models — by their probabilistic nature — do not straightforwardly satisfy that assumption. This paper introduces ST-T1024, an open standard (Apache 2.0) for deterministic embedded AI inference that replaces stochastic transformer inference with a fully deterministic, Finite State Machine (FSM)-orchestrated, ternary-quantized pipeline.
This paper makes a specific, bounded claim: ST-T1024's architecture possesses technical properties — bounded worst-case execution time, traceable state transitions, tile-level freedom from interference, and ASIL-decomposable structure — that satisfy the technical requirements ISO 26262 sets for the components it certifies. This is a claim about architectural properties, demonstrable by inspection of the design. It is not a claim that ST-T1024 has been certified, or that certification can be granted on the basis of this paper alone. Certification is a process outcome, requiring a documented safety case, independent third-party assessment, and organizational process compliance (ISO 26262 Parts 2, 6, 8, 9) that lies outside the scope of an architecture specification. This paper's purpose is to establish that the architectural foundation for that process already exists.
With a worst-case execution time of ≤800 ns (architectural target; see companion benchmarking document for current simulated-vs-hardware-validated status), an order-of-magnitude energy reduction versus cloud-based inference, and a bounded-output design that eliminates the stochastic hallucination mechanism, ST-T1024 offers a practical architectural foundation for certifiable AI in automotive, aerospace, and industrial safety-critical systems.
Keywords — ISO 26262, functional safety, deterministic AI, embedded systems, ASIL, RISC-V, FSM, ternary quantization, safety-critical systems, automotive AI
Introduction
The automotive industry is integrating AI into Advanced Driver Assistance Systems (ADAS) and autonomous driving functions. A structural tension exists: ISO 26262 was built around the assumption that safety-critical software behaves deterministically — given the same inputs, a correctly implemented function produces the same outputs, and that behavior can be formally specified and verified. Stochastic AI inference, by contrast, is fundamentally probabilistic in its standard form.
This paper presents ST-T1024 — an open standard whose architecture is designed to resolve that tension at the technical level. It does not claim to resolve the organizational and procedural requirements of ISO 26262 compliance, which remain separate work.
