3.1 Determinism
ST-T1024's architecture enforces determinism at every level:
Temperature = 0.0 — no stochastic sampling
FSM cycle counter — WCET ≤ 800 ns (architectural target; hardware validation status tracked separately)
Ternary arithmetic — no floating-point variance
Fixed memory layout — 75% ROM, 25% SRAM
3.2 Traceability
Every decision is architecturally auditable:
FSM state transitions are logged
FIS routing is deterministic and rule-based
Outputs are either a bounded-domain answer or an explicit 0x-AMBIG signal — no free-form generation outside a tile's defined scope
3.3 Freedom from Interference
ST-T1024 uses N independent domain tiles. Only one tile activates per query; all others are gated to 0V. This is designed to eliminate resource contention and to ensure that a failure in one tile cannot propagate to others — an architectural property relevant to, but not by itself sufficient for, ASIL decomposition, which also requires a documented independence analysis.
3.4 ASIL Decomposition
ISO 26262 permits ASIL decomposition when independent safety mechanisms are demonstrated and documented. ST-T1024's tile-based architecture is structured to support this:
Lower-ASIL perception units — each tile handles a specific domain
Higher-ASIL monitor unit — the FSM supervises all transitions
Algorithm diversification — different tiles may use different internal logic
Whether a specific implementation qualifies for a specific decomposition still requires the formal independence and safety analysis ISO 26262 Part 9 specifies. This section describes the architectural feature that would support such an analysis, not a completed decomposition.
What Remains: The Certification Process
Satisfying the technical properties in Sections 2–3 is necessary but not sufficient for certification. ISO 26262 additionally requires, separate from architecture:
A documented safety case, including hazard analysis and FMEDA
Independent third-party assessment (e.g., TÜV, UL)
Organizational safety management process compliance (Part 2)
Verification and tool-qualification evidence (Part 8)
Formal ASIL decomposition analysis, application-specific (Part 9)
None of these have been completed for ST-T1024 as of this writing. This paper's contribution is the architectural foundation described in Sections 2–3, which is intended to make that subsequent process more direct — not to substitute for it.
