"AI and functional safety, as conventionally practiced, are difficult to reconcile because standard AI inference is fundamentally probabilistic."
ST-T1024's architecture is one way to close that gap at the technical level. Closing it at the certification level is the work described in Section 4.
Conclusion
ST-T1024 is a deterministic AI inference architecture whose properties — bounded WCET, traceable state transitions, tile-level freedom from interference, and ASIL-decomposable structure — satisfy the technical requirements ISO 26262 sets for the components it certifies. By replacing stochastic inference with a deterministic, FSM-orchestrated, ternary-quantized pipeline, it establishes, at the architectural level:
Determinism
Traceability
Freedom from interference
ASIL-decomposition-ready structure
With an architectural WCET target of ≤800 ns, a simulated multi-order-of-magnitude energy reduction per query (see companion benchmarking document for current validation status), and a bounded-output design, ST-T1024 offers a practical architectural foundation toward certifiable AI in automotive, aerospace, and industrial safety-critical systems.
The architecture is open. The properties are demonstrable now. The certification process — documented safety case, independent assessment, organizational compliance — is the next, separate body of work, and this paper is an invitation to undertake it jointly with functional safety experts and certification bodies.
